<P>But as for the Brethren, We need not go to them, to make a &s;econd Speech, now to ask leave to with-draw, and to render an ac|count to every impertinent Talker who thinks the man Married to him, and that his bed is broke into, or that there's no ju&s;t rea&s;on for a divorce.</P>
<P>Moreover, &s;ome people are forever di&s;&s;atisfied; neither con|veniencies of Habitation, liking the others Mini&s;try, profiting under it, or di&s;like of &s;ome Cu&s;toms and Practices which he would willingly be rid of the light of, can &s;atisfy. And what mu&s;t the grieved per&s;on do further in this ca&s;e? Why, truly he has done his duty, and may hear and communicate, where God and his own &s;ober Con&s;cience directs him. No<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> ought any Mini&s;ter of Chri&s;t, to reject his claim to the Lords T<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">ble with him.</P>
